    <!-- ===== ELIGIBILITY PAGE ===== -->
    <div class="page" id="page-eligibility">
        <div class="eligibility-hero">
            <h1>Eligibility & Guidelines</h1>
            <p>Learn who can donate blood, the criteria involved, and the facts behind common myths.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="eligibility-body">
            <div class="elig-grid">
                <div class="elig-card">
                    <h3>✅ Who Can Donate</h3>
                    <ul class="elig-list">
                        <li>Age between 18 and 65 years</li>
                        <li>Weight at least 50 kg (110 lbs)</li>
                        <li>Hemoglobin level ≥ 12.5 g/dL</li>
                        <li>In good general health on day of donation</li>
                        <li>Blood pressure: 90/60 to 160/100 mmHg</li>
                        <li>Pulse rate between 60–100 beats per minute</li>
                        <li>Temperature below 37.5°C</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-card">
                    <h3>❌ Who Cannot Donate</h3>
                    <ul class="elig-list">
                        <li class="no">Donated blood within the last 3 months</li>
                        <li class="no">Pregnant or breastfeeding</li>
                        <li class="no">Had tattoo/piercing in last 6 months</li>
                        <li class="no">Currently on antibiotics or blood thinners</li>
                        <li class="no">History of HIV, Hepatitis B or C</li>
                        <li class="no">Recent surgery in the past 6 months</li>
                        <li class="no">Fever, cold, or flu in last 2 weeks</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-card">
                    <h3>⏱ Time Gap Guidelines</h3>
                    <ul class="elig-list">
                        <li>Whole blood: every 3 months (56 days minimum)</li>
                        <li>Platelets: every 2 weeks, up to 24 times/year</li>
                        <li>Plasma: every 28 days</li>
                        <li>Double red cells: every 4 months</li>
                        <li>Allow your body to fully recover between donations</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-card">
                    <h3>🍎 Before Donation – Tips</h3>
                    <ul class="elig-list">
                        <li>Drink plenty of water (at least 500ml) before donating</li>
                        <li>Eat a healthy, iron-rich meal beforehand</li>
                        <li>Avoid fatty foods 4 hours before donation</li>
                        <li>Get a good night's sleep</li>
                        <li>Wear comfortable, loose-sleeved clothing</li>
                        <li>Avoid strenuous exercise on donation day</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="myths-section">
                <h2>🔍 Myths vs Facts</h2>
                <div class="myth-item">
                    <span class="myth-tag">Myth</span>
                    <h4>Donating blood is painful and dangerous.</h4>
                    <p><span class="fact-tag">Fact</span> The process is very safe. A tiny needle prick causes minimal
                        discomfort, and donors typically feel fine within minutes. Strict sterile procedures are
                        followed.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="myth-item">
                    <span class="myth-tag">Myth</span>
                    <h4>You can get HIV or other diseases from donating blood.</h4>
                    <p><span class="fact-tag">Fact</span> All equipment used is sterile and single-use. There is
                        absolutely zero risk of contracting any disease from the donation process itself.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="myth-item">
                    <span class="myth-tag">Myth</span>
                    <h4>Donating blood weakens your body permanently.</h4>
                    <p><span class="fact-tag">Fact</span> The body replaces donated plasma within 24 hours, and red
                        blood cells are fully replenished within 4–6 weeks. Regular donors are among the healthiest
                        people.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="myth-item">
                    <span class="myth-tag">Myth</span>
                    <h4>People with diabetes or high blood pressure cannot donate.</h4>
                    <p><span class="fact-tag">Fact</span> Many people with controlled diabetes or well-managed blood
                        pressure can donate. A quick screening at the donation center will determine eligibility.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="myth-item">
                    <span class="myth-tag">Myth</span>
                    <h4>I have a rare blood type, so my donation doesn't matter.</h4>
                    <p><span class="fact-tag">Fact</span> Rare blood types are actually more critically needed! Patients
                        with rare types can only receive matching blood, making your donation uniquely life-saving.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

